{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504971","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504971"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:23:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:23:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2391"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2391"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.2,0.06,0.06,0.39]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2391"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43993"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2391"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2391"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28981"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1223"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1547"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1564"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35885"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42481"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43138"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43993","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43993"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old G1P0 woman presents to her General Practitioner for evaluation of acne on her face and chest. She has no itch or scaling. She is concerned about facial scarring and is determined to get treatment. She has a three-year history of mild acne and has had previous treatment with topical benzoyl peroxide with minimal clinical improvement. She has no other significant medical history and does not take any regular medications except for a pregnancy multivitamin. She is currently 18 weeks pregnant and with an uneventful normal pregnancy thus far.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her BMI is 23 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. There are visible open comedones on her face and upper chest, and pustules can be observed from several comedones. The comedones are surrounded by generalised erythema. She does not complain of any tenderness on these skin lesions but feels uncomfortable when wearing clothes over these lesions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical benzoyl peroxide","Topical isotretinoin","Oral tetracyclines","Oral spironolactone","Oral erythromycin"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAcne vulgaris is a common skin disease that appears as comedones in common locations such as the face, chest and back. These comedones can develop into inflammatory pustules or papules in moderate-severe cases, classified as inflammatory acne. They often requires oral antibiotics due to the risk of further complications such as scarring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical benzoyl peroxide\u003C/strong\u003E has comedolytic and bactericidal effects that are used to treat mild acne. This patient has already tried this topical medication and the acne has progressed to moderate-severe inflammatory acne.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral\u003C/strong\u003E antibiotics such as \u003Cstrong\u003Etetracyclines\u003C/strong\u003E are used to treat acne via an anti-inflammatory action. However, tetracyclines are teratogenic and are contraindicated in pregnant and breastfeeding women. Their use is associated with permanent teeth discolouration and enamel hypoplasia. Patients that require oral antibiotics may use \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral erythromycin\u003C/strong\u003E that is safe in pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral spironolactone \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Etopical isotretinoin \u003C/strong\u003Eare alternative acne treatments, however, their use is also contraindicated in pregnancy and should be avoided.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Topical benzoyl peroxide is usually sufficient treatment for mild acne.","Tetracyclines, spironolactone and isotretinoin are contraindicated in pregnancy and should be avoided in the treatment of acne."],"references":["Williams HC, Dellavalle RP, Garner S. Acne vulgaris. Lancet. 2012;379:361. Available at: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(11)60321-8/abstract","Zaenglein AL, Pathy AL, Schlosser BJ, et al. Guidelines of care for the management of acne vulgaris. J Am Acad Dermatol. 2016;74:945. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26897386/","Aselton P, Jick H, Milunsky A, et al. First-trimester drug use and congenital disorders. Obstet Gynecol. 1985;65:451. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/3982720/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28981"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2391"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28981"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-03T22:27:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-09T19:45:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2391"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43993"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":n